rld, she shows how every country can provide citizens with the basics to have a decent life and be able to contribute to society. But we owe each other more than this. A more generous and inclusive society would also share more risks collectively and ask everyone to contribute for as long as they can so that everyone can fulfill their potential. What We Owe Each Other identifies the key elements of a better social contract that recognizes our interdependencies, supports and invests more in each other, and expects more of individuals in return.Powerful, hopeful, and thought-provoking, What We Owe Each Other provides practical solutions to current challenges and demonstrates how we can build a better society-together.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHuman services. 0aPublic welfare. 0aSocial contract. 0aSocial ethics. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh  aAffordable Care Act.  aCOVID-19.  aCovid.  aObamacare.  aadult learning.  acarbon footprint.  achildcare.  aeconomics and women.  aeducation.  aelder care.  aeldercare.  aelderly care.  aenvironmental policies.  aenvironmental protection.  aenvironmentalism.  aflexible work schedule.  afuture generations.  afuture of work.  aindependent living.  aintergenerational.  ajob benefits.  ajob flexibility.  ajob security.  alife expectancy.  aretirement age.  aretirement planning.  aretirement.  asocial policies.  asocial policy.  asocial safety net.  aunemployment.  auniversal health care.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691220277zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691220277423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/